<dl id="n09018f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09018f">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09018f"> 18(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> night, distance, <font color="green">[sordity]</font> / checks to hum. progress</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> The alternation of day and <mark>night is a check on the freedom of human activity</mark> which must go the way of other spatial and temporal checks. In the long run I think that all that applied physics can do for us is abolish these checks. It enables us to possess more, travel more, and communicate more. <small> J. B. S. Haldane, <a name="DAED" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DAED"><cite title="source">Dedalus</cite></a> (1923) 19</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
